WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.720 --> 00:00:06.510
Prof: So this is a very
exciting day for me,

00:00:06.510 --> 00:00:09.976
because today,
we're going to start quantum

00:00:09.976 --> 00:00:15.010
mechanics and that's all we'll
do till the end of the term.

00:00:15.010 --> 00:00:19.780
Now I've got bad news and good
news.

00:00:19.780 --> 00:00:24.393
The bad news is that it's a
subject that's kind of hard to

00:00:24.393 --> 00:00:27.955
follow intuitively,
and the good news is that

00:00:27.955 --> 00:00:30.950
nobody can follow it
intuitively.

00:00:30.950 --> 00:00:33.474
Richard Feynman,
one of the big figures in

00:00:33.474 --> 00:00:36.245
physics, used to say,
"No one understands

00:00:36.245 --> 00:00:37.970
quantum mechanics."
 

00:00:37.970 --> 00:00:40.574
So in some sense,
the pressure is off for you

00:00:40.574 --> 00:00:44.125
guys, because I don't get it and
you don't get it and Feynman

00:00:44.125 --> 00:00:45.250
doesn't get it.
 

00:00:45.250 --> 00:00:48.870
The point is, here is my goal.
 

00:00:48.870 --> 00:00:52.703
Right now, I'm the only one who
doesn't understand quantum

00:00:52.703 --> 00:00:53.510
mechanics.
 

00:00:53.510 --> 00:00:56.730
In about seven days,
all of you will be unable to

00:00:56.730 --> 00:00:58.810
understand quantum mechanics.
 

00:00:58.810 --> 00:01:02.579
Then you can go back and spread
your ignorance everywhere else.

00:01:02.579 --> 00:01:06.560
That's the only legacy a
teacher can want.

00:01:06.560 --> 00:01:09.959
All right, so that's the spirit
in which we are doing this.

00:01:09.959 --> 00:01:13.400
I want you to think about this
as a real adventure.

00:01:13.400 --> 00:01:16.640
Try to think beyond the exams
and grades and everything.

00:01:16.640 --> 00:01:20.762
It's one of the biggest
discoveries in physics,

00:01:20.762 --> 00:01:26.317
in science, and it's marvelous
how people even figured out this

00:01:26.317 --> 00:01:28.379
is what's going on.
 

00:01:28.379 --> 00:01:31.980
So I want to tell you in some
fashion, but not strictly

00:01:31.980 --> 00:01:33.379
historical fashion.
 

00:01:33.379 --> 00:01:36.870
Purely historical fashion is
pedagogically not the best way,

00:01:36.870 --> 00:01:39.920
because you go through all the
wrong tracks and get confused,

00:01:39.920 --> 00:01:42.610
and there are a lot of battles
going on.

00:01:42.610 --> 00:01:46.061
When the dust settles down,
a certain picture emerges and

00:01:46.061 --> 00:01:48.650
that's the picture I wanted to
give you.

00:01:48.650 --> 00:01:52.372
In a way, I will appeal to
experiments that were perhaps

00:01:52.372 --> 00:01:55.959
not done in the sequence in
which I describe them,

00:01:55.959 --> 00:01:58.569
but we know that if you did
them, this is what the answer

00:01:58.569 --> 00:02:00.498
would be,
and everyone agrees,

00:02:00.498 --> 00:02:03.170
and they are the simplest
experiments.

00:02:03.170 --> 00:02:07.930
All right, so today we're going
to shoot down Newtonian

00:02:07.930 --> 00:02:10.840
mechanics and Maxwell's theory.
 

00:02:10.840 --> 00:02:12.060
So we are like the press.
 

00:02:12.060 --> 00:02:14.990
We build somebody up,
only to destroy them.

00:02:14.990 --> 00:02:17.169
Built up Newton;
shot down.

00:02:17.169 --> 00:02:20.598
Built up Maxwell;
going to get shot down.

00:02:20.598 --> 00:02:24.795
So again, I have tried to drill
into all of you the notion that

00:02:24.795 --> 00:02:28.316
people get shot down because
somebody else does a new

00:02:28.316 --> 00:02:31.972
experiment that probes an
entirely new regime which had

00:02:31.972 --> 00:02:33.800
not been seen before.
 

00:02:33.800 --> 00:02:35.340
So it's not that people were
dumb;

00:02:35.340 --> 00:02:38.615
it's that given the information
they had, they built the best

00:02:38.615 --> 00:02:39.979
theory that they could.
 

00:02:39.979 --> 00:02:42.270
And if you give me more
additional information,

00:02:42.270 --> 00:02:45.057
more refined measurements,
something to the tenth decimal

00:02:45.057 --> 00:02:47.150
place, I may have to change what
I do.

00:02:47.150 --> 00:02:48.568
That's how it's going to be.
 

00:02:48.568 --> 00:02:50.348
So there's always going to
be--for example,

00:02:50.348 --> 00:02:53.366
in the big collider,
people are expecting to see new

00:02:53.366 --> 00:02:55.798
stuff,
hopefully stuff that hasn't

00:02:55.798 --> 00:02:58.538
been explained by any existing
theory.

00:02:58.538 --> 00:03:00.399
And we all want that,
because we want some

00:03:00.399 --> 00:03:02.438
excitement, we want to find out
new things.

00:03:02.438 --> 00:03:05.312
The best way not to worry about
your old theories is to not do

00:03:05.312 --> 00:03:06.159
any experiments.
 

00:03:06.159 --> 00:03:08.379
Then you can go home.
 

00:03:08.379 --> 00:03:09.590
But that's not how it goes.
 

00:03:09.590 --> 00:03:11.710
You probe more and more stuff.
 

00:03:11.710 --> 00:03:15.573
So here's what you do to find
out what's wrong with

00:03:15.573 --> 00:03:19.360
electrodynamics,
I mean, with Maxwell's theory.

00:03:19.360 --> 00:03:22.938
It all starts with a double
slit experiment.

00:03:22.938 --> 00:03:30.514
You have this famous double
slit and some waves are coming

00:03:30.514 --> 00:03:32.110
from here.
 

00:03:32.110 --> 00:03:35.970
You have some wavelength l.
 

00:03:35.970 --> 00:03:43.974
Then in the back,
I'm going to put a photographic

00:03:43.974 --> 00:03:45.310
plate.
 

00:03:45.310 --> 00:03:47.535
A photographic plate,
as you know,

00:03:47.535 --> 00:03:51.447
is made of these tiny little
pixels which change color when

00:03:51.447 --> 00:03:54.818
light hits them and then you see
your picture.

00:03:54.818 --> 00:03:59.110
And that's the way to detect
light, a perfectly good way to

00:03:59.110 --> 00:04:00.218
detect light.
 

00:04:00.218 --> 00:04:03.587
So first thing we do is,
we block this hole or this

00:04:03.587 --> 00:04:04.060
slit.
 

00:04:04.060 --> 00:04:05.860
This is slit 1 and slit 2.
 

00:04:05.860 --> 00:04:09.594
We block this and we look at
what happened to the

00:04:09.594 --> 00:04:11.229
photographic plate.
 

00:04:11.229 --> 00:04:17.660
What you will find is that the
region in front of it got pretty

00:04:17.660 --> 00:04:20.500
dark,
or let's say had an image,

00:04:20.500 --> 00:04:23.750
whereas if you go too far from
the slit,

00:04:23.750 --> 00:04:25.769
you don't see anything.
 

00:04:25.769 --> 00:04:32.629
So that's called intensity,
when one is open.

00:04:32.629 --> 00:04:39.589
Then you close that guy and you
get similar pattern.

00:04:39.589 --> 00:04:43.560
Then you open both.
 

00:04:43.560 --> 00:04:47.721
Then I told you,
you may expect that,

00:04:47.721 --> 00:04:54.774
but what you get instead--let's
see, I've got to pick my graph

00:04:54.774 --> 00:05:00.439
properly-- is something that
looks like this.

00:05:00.439 --> 00:05:03.586
Now that is the phenomenon of
interference,

00:05:03.586 --> 00:05:05.759
which we studied last time.
 

00:05:05.759 --> 00:05:07.259
So what's the part that's funny?
 

00:05:07.259 --> 00:05:11.781
What's the part that makes you
wonder is if you go to some

00:05:11.781 --> 00:05:15.670
location like this,
go to a location like this.

00:05:15.670 --> 00:05:20.389
This used to be a bright
location when one slit was open.

00:05:20.389 --> 00:05:23.081
It was also a bright location,
reasonably bright,

00:05:23.081 --> 00:05:24.819
when the other slit was open.
 

00:05:24.819 --> 00:05:28.839
But when both are open,
it becomes dark.

00:05:28.839 --> 00:05:31.374
You can ask,
"How can it be that I open

00:05:31.374 --> 00:05:33.259
two windows, room gets darker?
 

00:05:33.259 --> 00:05:35.728
Why doesn't it happen there,
and why does it happen

00:05:35.728 --> 00:05:36.370
here?"
 

00:05:36.370 --> 00:05:39.834
The answer is that you're
sending light of definite

00:05:39.834 --> 00:05:42.329
wavelength and the wave
function,

00:05:42.329 --> 00:05:44.829
Y, whatever measures the
oscillation,

00:05:44.829 --> 00:05:46.459
maybe electric field,
magnetic field,

00:05:46.459 --> 00:05:48.920
obeys the superposition
principle.

00:05:48.920 --> 00:05:53.151
And when two slits are open,
what you're supposed to add is

00:05:53.151 --> 00:05:56.069
the electric field,
not the intensity.

00:05:56.069 --> 00:06:01.105
The intensity is proportional
to the square of the electric

00:06:01.105 --> 00:06:01.800
field.
 

00:06:01.800 --> 00:06:03.769
You don't add E^(2);
you add E.

00:06:03.769 --> 00:06:05.920
E is what obeys the wave
equation.

00:06:05.920 --> 00:06:08.584
E_1 is a
solution, E_2

00:06:08.584 --> 00:06:09.360
is a solution.
 

00:06:09.360 --> 00:06:11.223
E_1
E_2 is a

00:06:11.223 --> 00:06:11.680
solution.
 

00:06:11.680 --> 00:06:14.153
No one tells you that if you
add the two sources,

00:06:14.153 --> 00:06:16.627
I_1
I_2 is going to be

00:06:16.627 --> 00:06:17.709
the final answer.
 

00:06:17.709 --> 00:06:19.959
The correct answer is to find
E_1

00:06:19.959 --> 00:06:21.980
E_2 and then
square that.

00:06:21.980 --> 00:06:22.863
But when you do
E_1

00:06:22.863 --> 00:06:24.579
E_2,
since E_1 and

00:06:24.579 --> 00:06:26.839
E_2 are not
necessarily positive definite,

00:06:26.839 --> 00:06:29.187
when you add them,
sometimes they can add with the

00:06:29.187 --> 00:06:31.043
same sign,
sometimes they can add with

00:06:31.043 --> 00:06:33.324
opposite signs,
and sometimes in between,

00:06:33.324 --> 00:06:34.829
so you get this pattern.
 

00:06:34.829 --> 00:06:36.560
So we're not surprised.
 

00:06:36.560 --> 00:06:39.192
And I've told you many times
why we don't see it when we open

00:06:39.192 --> 00:06:40.690
big windows,
first of all,

00:06:40.690 --> 00:06:43.971
when you open a window,
the slit sizes are all many,

00:06:43.971 --> 00:06:47.649
many, many million times bigger
than the wavelength of light.

00:06:47.649 --> 00:06:50.040
Plus the light is not just one
color and so on.

00:06:50.040 --> 00:06:52.740
So you don't pick up these
oscillations.

00:06:52.740 --> 00:06:55.339
These oscillations are very
fine.

00:06:55.339 --> 00:06:57.940
I draw them this way so you can
see them.

00:06:57.940 --> 00:07:00.476
In a real life thing,
if this were really windows and

00:07:00.476 --> 00:07:02.430
this was the back wall of your
house,

00:07:02.430 --> 00:07:04.850
the oscillations would be so
tightly spaced,

00:07:04.850 --> 00:07:07.656
I'll just draw some of them,
that the human eye cannot

00:07:07.656 --> 00:07:09.139
detect these oscillations.
 

00:07:09.139 --> 00:07:11.060
It will only pick up the
average value.

00:07:11.060 --> 00:07:15.326
The average value will in fact
look like I_1

00:07:15.326 --> 00:07:16.850
I_2.
 

00:07:16.850 --> 00:07:18.540
So this is all very nice.
 

00:07:18.540 --> 00:07:21.740
This is how Young discovered
that light is a wave.

00:07:21.740 --> 00:07:24.290
By doing the interference,
I told you,

00:07:24.290 --> 00:07:26.843
he could even find a
wavelength, because it's a

00:07:26.843 --> 00:07:30.285
simple matter of geometry to see
where you've got to go for two

00:07:30.285 --> 00:07:31.339
guys to cancel.
 

00:07:31.339 --> 00:07:34.687
And once you know that angle,
you know where on that screen

00:07:34.687 --> 00:07:36.879
you will get a minimum or a
maximum.

00:07:36.879 --> 00:07:37.819
So you've got the wavelength.
 

00:07:37.819 --> 00:07:39.230
He didn't know what was doing
it.

00:07:39.230 --> 00:07:41.105
He didn't know it was
electromagnetic,

00:07:41.105 --> 00:07:42.779
but you can get the wavelength.
 

00:07:42.779 --> 00:07:47.170
So interference is a hallmark
of waves.

00:07:47.170 --> 00:07:49.009
Any wave will do interference.
 

00:07:49.009 --> 00:07:51.050
Water will do the same thing.
 

00:07:51.050 --> 00:07:55.870
For example,
this is your beach house.

00:07:55.870 --> 00:07:57.639
You've got some ocean front
property.

00:07:57.639 --> 00:08:01.730
This is a little lagoon and you
have a wall to keep the ocean

00:08:01.730 --> 00:08:03.639
waves out of your mansion.
 

00:08:03.639 --> 00:08:09.750
And then suddenly one day,
there is a break in the wall.

00:08:09.750 --> 00:08:12.855
Break in the wall,
the waves start coming in and

00:08:12.855 --> 00:08:16.819
you're having a little boat
here, trying to get some rest.

00:08:16.819 --> 00:08:20.939
The boat starts jumping up and
down because of the waves.

00:08:20.939 --> 00:08:22.709
So you have two options.
 

00:08:22.709 --> 00:08:25.651
One options is to go and try to
plug that thing,

00:08:25.651 --> 00:08:28.466
but let's say you've got no
bricks, no mortar,

00:08:28.466 --> 00:08:29.970
no time, no nothing.
 

00:08:29.970 --> 00:08:31.329
You've just got a sledgehammer.
 

00:08:31.329 --> 00:08:35.558
What you can do,
you can make another hole.

00:08:35.558 --> 00:08:38.452
If these water waves are a
definite wavelength,

00:08:38.452 --> 00:08:41.344
only in that case,
you can make another hole so

00:08:41.344 --> 00:08:43.860
these two add up to 0 where you
are.

00:08:43.860 --> 00:08:46.384
Similarly, if you don't like
the music your roommate's

00:08:46.384 --> 00:08:48.277
playing,
if you can manufacture the same

00:08:48.277 --> 00:08:51.761
music with a phase shift of p,
you can add them together,

00:08:51.761 --> 00:08:52.639
you get 0.
 

00:08:52.639 --> 00:08:55.996
But you've got to figure out
what the roommate's about to do

00:08:55.996 --> 00:08:58.158
and be synchronous with the
person,

00:08:58.158 --> 00:09:01.830
but get a wavelength of p--I
mean, a phase shift of p.

00:09:01.830 --> 00:09:03.278
So you can cancel waves.
 

00:09:03.278 --> 00:09:06.740
That's the idea behind all
kinds of noise cancelation,

00:09:06.740 --> 00:09:10.333
but you've got to know the
exact phase of the one signal

00:09:10.333 --> 00:09:12.490
that you're trying to cancel.
 

00:09:12.490 --> 00:09:15.898
All right, so everything looks
good for Maxwell,

00:09:15.898 --> 00:09:19.379
till you start doing the
following experiment.

00:09:19.379 --> 00:09:23.822
You make the source of light,
whatever it is,

00:09:23.822 --> 00:09:26.450
dimmer and dimmer,
okay?

00:09:26.450 --> 00:09:29.500
So you may not be able to turn
down the brightness.

00:09:29.500 --> 00:09:31.472
Maybe you can,
maybe you cannot,

00:09:31.472 --> 00:09:35.610
but you can imagine moving the
source further and further back.

00:09:35.610 --> 00:09:39.773
You move it further and further
back, you know the energy falls

00:09:39.773 --> 00:09:42.929
like 1/r^(2),
so you can make it weak.

00:09:42.929 --> 00:09:44.559
So here's what we try to do.
 

00:09:44.559 --> 00:09:48.548
We put a new photographic film.
 

00:09:48.548 --> 00:09:54.673
We take the light source way
back, then we wait for something

00:09:54.673 --> 00:09:55.899
to happen.
 

00:09:55.899 --> 00:09:59.009
We come the next morning,
we find there's a very faint

00:09:59.009 --> 00:10:02.413
pattern that's taken place over
night, because the film got

00:10:02.413 --> 00:10:04.409
exposed all through the night.
 

00:10:04.409 --> 00:10:07.000
Now we can see a faint pattern.
 

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:10.629
Then you go and turn it down
even more.

00:10:10.629 --> 00:10:14.340
You come back the next day,
you look at the film.

00:10:14.340 --> 00:10:18.251
You find no pattern,
just two or three spots which

00:10:18.251 --> 00:10:19.850
have been exposed.
 

00:10:19.850 --> 00:10:23.364
If you look at the screen--so
let me show you a view of the

00:10:23.364 --> 00:10:23.908
screen.
 

00:10:23.908 --> 00:10:27.071
Normally you will have bright
and dark and bright and dark

00:10:27.071 --> 00:10:30.399
patterns on the back wall if you
turn on a powerful light.

00:10:30.399 --> 00:10:33.119
But I'm telling you,
if you have a really weak

00:10:33.119 --> 00:10:36.684
source, you just find that got
exposed, that got exposed and

00:10:36.684 --> 00:10:38.620
that got exposed,
that's it.

00:10:38.620 --> 00:10:44.240
Only three points on the film
are exposed, and that is very

00:10:44.240 --> 00:10:45.210
strange.
 

00:10:45.210 --> 00:10:49.568
Because if light is a wave,
no matter how weak it is,

00:10:49.568 --> 00:10:52.418
it should hit the entire
screen.

00:10:52.418 --> 00:10:53.889
It cannot hit certain parts of
it.

00:10:53.889 --> 00:10:56.918
Waves don't hit certain parts.
 

00:10:56.918 --> 00:10:58.580
In fact, how can it hit just
one?

00:10:58.580 --> 00:11:00.835
For example,
if you make it weak enough,

00:11:00.835 --> 00:11:03.553
you can have a situation where
in the whole day,

00:11:03.553 --> 00:11:05.000
you just get one hit.
 

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:07.399
So something is hitting that
screen and it's not a wave,

00:11:07.399 --> 00:11:11.008
because a wave is spread out
over its full transverse

00:11:11.008 --> 00:11:14.816
dimension,
but this is hitting one point

00:11:14.816 --> 00:11:16.320
on the screen.
 

00:11:16.320 --> 00:11:20.166
So you make further
observations and you find out

00:11:20.166 --> 00:11:25.134
that what happens here is there
is a certain amount of momentum

00:11:25.134 --> 00:11:28.740
and energy are delivered during
that hit.

00:11:28.740 --> 00:11:32.235
If you could measure the recoil
of that film,

00:11:32.235 --> 00:11:36.764
you will find it gets hit and
the momentum you get per hit

00:11:36.764 --> 00:11:40.259
looks like ℏ x
k.

00:11:40.259 --> 00:11:42.120
I'll tell you what it means.
 

00:11:42.120 --> 00:11:44.735
This is 2p
h/l,

00:11:44.735 --> 00:11:48.033
where l is your
wavelength, h is the new

00:11:48.033 --> 00:11:50.649
constant called the Planck's
constant.

00:11:50.649 --> 00:11:59.990
And its value is 6.6 x 10^(-34
)joule seconds.

00:11:59.990 --> 00:12:03.259
You also find,
every time you get a hit here,

00:12:03.259 --> 00:12:06.330
there's a certain energy
deposited here and the energy

00:12:06.330 --> 00:12:09.748
deposited here happens to be
ℏw where

00:12:09.748 --> 00:12:12.345
w,
as you know,

00:12:12.345 --> 00:12:15.620
is 2pf.
 

00:12:15.620 --> 00:12:18.408
So here's what I'm telling you.
 

00:12:18.408 --> 00:12:23.807
If you send light of a known
frequency and known wavelength

00:12:23.807 --> 00:12:28.618
and you make it extremely dim,
and you put a photographic

00:12:28.618 --> 00:12:31.558
plate and you wait till
something happens,

00:12:31.558 --> 00:12:35.279
what happens is not a thin blur
over the whole screen.

00:12:35.279 --> 00:12:38.259
What happens is a hit at one
location.

00:12:38.259 --> 00:12:41.429
And what comes to that location
seems to be a bundle of energy

00:12:41.429 --> 00:12:42.470
and momentum,
i.e.

00:12:42.470 --> 00:12:44.418
a particle, right?
 

00:12:44.418 --> 00:12:47.186
When something hits you in the
face, it's got energy,

00:12:47.186 --> 00:12:48.250
it's got momentum.
 

00:12:48.250 --> 00:12:51.423
So this film is getting hit at
one point by a particle,

00:12:51.423 --> 00:12:54.893
and what we can say about the
particle is the following - it

00:12:54.893 --> 00:12:56.009
has a momentum.
 

00:12:56.009 --> 00:12:59.668
It has the same momentum every
time.

00:12:59.668 --> 00:13:00.908
You get this hit,
you get that hit,

00:13:00.908 --> 00:13:01.600
you get that hit.
 

00:13:01.600 --> 00:13:05.485
As long as you don't screw
around with the wavelength of

00:13:05.485 --> 00:13:08.734
incoming light,
the momentum and energy of each

00:13:08.734 --> 00:13:10.428
packet is identical.
 

00:13:10.428 --> 00:13:12.610
It's more than saying light
seems to be made of particles.

00:13:12.610 --> 00:13:15.576
Made of particles,
each one of them carries an

00:13:15.576 --> 00:13:19.136
energy and momentum that's
absolutely correlated with a

00:13:19.136 --> 00:13:21.048
wavelength and frequency.
 

00:13:21.048 --> 00:13:30.561
Now let me remind you that
w = kc for light

00:13:30.561 --> 00:13:31.918
waves.
 

00:13:31.918 --> 00:13:33.740
We've done this many,
many times.

00:13:33.740 --> 00:13:36.476
That means the energy,
which is

00:13:36.476 --> 00:13:40.580
ℏw,
and the momentum is

00:13:40.580 --> 00:13:44.774
ℏk,
are related by the relation

00:13:44.774 --> 00:13:46.600
E = pc.
 

00:13:46.600 --> 00:13:50.687
So these particles have a
momentum which is related to

00:13:50.687 --> 00:13:53.620
energy by the formula E =
pc.

00:13:53.620 --> 00:13:58.275
When you go back to your
relativity notes from the last

00:13:58.275 --> 00:14:03.019
semester, you'll find the
following relation is true.

00:14:03.019 --> 00:14:06.724
Any particle,
E^(2) = c^(2)p^(2)

00:14:06.724 --> 00:14:09.340
m^(2)c^(4).
 

00:14:09.340 --> 00:14:14.668
That's the connection between
energy and momentum.

00:14:14.668 --> 00:14:19.450
Therefore this looks like a
particle whose m is 0.

00:14:19.450 --> 00:14:23.419
If m is 0, E = pc.
 

00:14:23.419 --> 00:14:26.048
So these particles are massless.
 

00:14:26.048 --> 00:14:29.581
They have no rest mass and you
know, something with no rest

00:14:29.581 --> 00:14:32.932
mass, if it is to have a
momentum, it must travel at the

00:14:32.932 --> 00:14:34.090
speed of light.
 

00:14:34.090 --> 00:14:38.355
Because normally,
the momentum of anything with

00:14:38.355 --> 00:14:41.509
mass is mv,
in the old days,

00:14:41.509 --> 00:14:44.850
divided by this,
after Einstein.

00:14:44.850 --> 00:14:48.428
And if you don't want to have
an m, and yet you want to

00:14:48.428 --> 00:14:51.068
have a p,
the only way it can happen is

00:14:51.068 --> 00:14:52.360
that v = c.
 

00:14:52.360 --> 00:14:54.597
Then you have 0/0,
there is some chance,

00:14:54.597 --> 00:14:57.408
and nature seems to take
advantage of that 0/0.

00:14:57.408 --> 00:14:59.529
These are the massless
particles.

00:14:59.529 --> 00:15:06.580
So these photons are massless
particles.

00:15:06.580 --> 00:15:08.490
So what is the shock?
 

00:15:08.490 --> 00:15:12.402
The shock is that light,
which you thought was a

00:15:12.402 --> 00:15:16.313
continuous wave,
is actually made up of discrete

00:15:16.313 --> 00:15:17.480
particles.
 

00:15:17.480 --> 00:15:20.076
In order to see them,
your light source has to be

00:15:20.076 --> 00:15:22.923
extremely weak,
because if you turn on a light

00:15:22.923 --> 00:15:26.274
source like this one,
millions of these photons come

00:15:26.274 --> 00:15:29.019
and the pattern is formed
instantaneously.

00:15:29.019 --> 00:15:31.558
The minute you turn on the
light, the film is exposed,

00:15:31.558 --> 00:15:34.350
you see these dark and light
and dark and light fringes,

00:15:34.350 --> 00:15:37.529
you think it's happening due to
waves that come instantaneously.

00:15:37.529 --> 00:15:41.708
But if you look under the hood,
every pattern is formed by tiny

00:15:41.708 --> 00:15:45.620
little dots which occur so fast
that you don't see them.

00:15:45.620 --> 00:15:49.168
That's where you've got to turn
down the intensity to actually

00:15:49.168 --> 00:15:49.808
see them.
 

00:15:49.808 --> 00:15:56.090
When you see that,
you see the corpuscular nature

00:15:56.090 --> 00:15:57.529
of light.
 

00:15:57.529 --> 00:16:00.456
But here is the problem - if
somebody told you light is made

00:16:00.456 --> 00:16:02.440
of particles and it's not
continuous,

00:16:02.440 --> 00:16:05.548
it's not so disturbing,
because water,

00:16:05.548 --> 00:16:08.807
which you think is continuous,
is actually made of water

00:16:08.807 --> 00:16:09.519
molecules.
 

00:16:09.519 --> 00:16:12.331
Everything that you think of as
continuous is made up of little

00:16:12.331 --> 00:16:15.522
molecules and in a bigger scale,
much bigger than the atomic or

00:16:15.522 --> 00:16:18.899
molecular size,
it looks like it's continuous.

00:16:18.899 --> 00:16:21.320
That's not the bad news.
 

00:16:21.320 --> 00:16:28.120
The bad news really has to do
with the fact that if you have

00:16:28.120 --> 00:16:34.490
these particles called photons,
if it really were a particle,

00:16:34.490 --> 00:16:38.110
namely a standard,
garden variety particle,

00:16:38.110 --> 00:16:39.879
what should you find?
 

00:16:39.879 --> 00:16:44.259
If you emit a particle from
here, and only one slit is open,

00:16:44.259 --> 00:16:48.416
it will take some path going
through the slit and it will

00:16:48.416 --> 00:16:49.529
come there.
 

00:16:49.529 --> 00:16:54.094
So let us say on a given day,
10 photons will come here,

00:16:54.094 --> 00:16:59.240
or let's say 4 photons will
come here, with this one closed.

00:16:59.240 --> 00:17:02.548
Then let's close this one and
open this one.

00:17:02.548 --> 00:17:06.160
In that, case,
maybe 3 photons will come here.

00:17:06.160 --> 00:17:09.328
Or let's say again, 4.
 

00:17:09.328 --> 00:17:18.170
Now I'm claiming that when both
are open, I get no photons.

00:17:18.170 --> 00:17:22.060
How can it be that when you
open a second hole,

00:17:22.060 --> 00:17:25.358
you get fewer particles coming
there?

00:17:25.358 --> 00:17:32.339
Particles normally either take
path number 1 or path number 2.

00:17:32.339 --> 00:17:34.980
Either this slit or this slit.
 

00:17:34.980 --> 00:17:38.165
To all the guys going this way,
they don't care if this slit is

00:17:38.165 --> 00:17:39.038
open or closed.
 

00:17:39.038 --> 00:17:40.630
They don't even know about the
other slit.

00:17:40.630 --> 00:17:43.567
They do their thing,
and guys going through this

00:17:43.567 --> 00:17:46.881
slit should do their thing,
therefore you should get a

00:17:46.881 --> 00:17:49.568
number equal to the sum,
but you don't.

00:17:49.568 --> 00:17:51.384
In other words,
for particles,

00:17:51.384 --> 00:17:53.388
which have definite
trajectories,

00:17:53.388 --> 00:17:56.834
opening a second slit should
not affect the number going

00:17:56.834 --> 00:17:58.650
through the first slit.
 

00:17:58.650 --> 00:17:59.269
Do you understand that?
 

00:17:59.269 --> 00:18:01.068
Particles are local.
 

00:18:01.068 --> 00:18:03.836
They're moving along and they
feel the local forces acting on

00:18:03.836 --> 00:18:05.588
them and they bend or twist or
turn.

00:18:05.588 --> 00:18:07.830
They don't really care what's
happening far away,

00:18:07.830 --> 00:18:09.980
whether a second slit may be
open or closed.

00:18:09.980 --> 00:18:13.686
Therefore logically,
the number coming here must be

00:18:13.686 --> 00:18:18.358
the sum of the number that would
come with 1 open and 2 open.

00:18:18.358 --> 00:18:20.550
How can you cancel a positive
number of particles coming

00:18:20.550 --> 00:18:22.902
somewhere with more positive
number of particles coming from

00:18:22.902 --> 00:18:23.660
somewhere else?
 

00:18:23.660 --> 00:18:25.500
How do you get a 0?
 

00:18:25.500 --> 00:18:29.598
That is where the wave comes in.
 

00:18:29.598 --> 00:18:32.463
The wave has no trouble knowing
how many slits are open,

00:18:32.463 --> 00:18:34.339
because the wave is not
localized.

00:18:34.339 --> 00:18:36.048
The wave comes like this.
 

00:18:36.048 --> 00:18:39.435
It can hit both the slits and
certainly cares about how many

00:18:39.435 --> 00:18:40.470
slits there are.
 

00:18:40.470 --> 00:18:43.500
Because there's only one,
that wave will go.

00:18:43.500 --> 00:18:45.628
You'll have some amplitude
here, which is kind of

00:18:45.628 --> 00:18:46.250
featureless.
 

00:18:46.250 --> 00:18:47.750
If that's open,
it will be featureless.

00:18:47.750 --> 00:18:53.348
If both are open,
there'll be interference.

00:18:53.348 --> 00:18:59.396
So we need that wave to
understand what the photon will

00:18:59.396 --> 00:19:01.760
do,
because when you send millions

00:19:01.760 --> 00:19:04.578
of photons and if you get the
pattern like this--

00:19:04.578 --> 00:19:07.881
let's say you sent lots and
lots of photons and you got a

00:19:07.881 --> 00:19:09.058
pattern like this.
 

00:19:09.058 --> 00:19:14.039
Now I'm going to send million 1
photon.

00:19:14.039 --> 00:19:17.690
Where will it go?
 

00:19:17.690 --> 00:19:20.088
We do not know where it will go.
 

00:19:20.088 --> 00:19:24.480
We only know that if you repeat
the experiment a million times,

00:19:24.480 --> 00:19:26.108
you get this pattern.
 

00:19:26.108 --> 00:19:28.990
But on the million 1th attempt,
where it will go,

00:19:28.990 --> 00:19:29.950
we don't know.
 

00:19:29.950 --> 00:19:34.098
We just know that the odds are
high when the function is high,

00:19:34.098 --> 00:19:36.876
or the intensity,
and the odds are low when the

00:19:36.876 --> 00:19:40.618
function is small and the odds
are 0 when the function is 0.

00:19:40.618 --> 00:19:45.734
So the role of the wave is to
determine the probability that

00:19:45.734 --> 00:19:50.328
the photon will arrive at some
point on the screen.

00:19:50.328 --> 00:19:54.854
And the probability is computed
by adding one wave function to

00:19:54.854 --> 00:19:57.970
another wave function and then
squaring.

00:19:57.970 --> 00:19:58.950
So you've got to be very clear.
 

00:19:58.950 --> 00:20:02.520
If someone says to you,
"Is the photon a particle

00:20:02.520 --> 00:20:03.328
or a wave?
 

00:20:03.328 --> 00:20:06.440
Make up your mind,
what is it?"

00:20:06.440 --> 00:20:10.491
Well, the answer is,
it's not going to be a yes or

00:20:10.491 --> 00:20:11.650
no question.
 

00:20:11.650 --> 00:20:13.267
People always ask you,
"Is matter made of

00:20:13.267 --> 00:20:14.703
particles or waves,
electron particles or

00:20:14.703 --> 00:20:15.278
waves?"
 

00:20:15.278 --> 00:20:18.448
Well, sometimes the vocabulary
we have is not big enough to

00:20:18.448 --> 00:20:20.359
describe what's really
happening.

00:20:20.359 --> 00:20:22.299
It is what it is.
 

00:20:22.299 --> 00:20:23.769
It is the following.
 

00:20:23.769 --> 00:20:27.770
It is a particle in the sense
that the entire energy is

00:20:27.770 --> 00:20:31.548
carried in these localized
places, unlike a wave.

00:20:31.548 --> 00:20:35.409
When the wave hits the beach,
the energy's over the entire

00:20:35.409 --> 00:20:36.288
wave front.
 

00:20:36.288 --> 00:20:39.210
This wave here is not a
physical wave.

00:20:39.210 --> 00:20:42.996
It does not carry any energy
and it's not even a property of

00:20:42.996 --> 00:20:44.279
a beam of photons.
 

00:20:44.279 --> 00:20:47.000
It's a property of one photon.
 

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:51.059
Here's what I want you to
understand - you send one photon

00:20:51.059 --> 00:20:54.194
at a time, many,
many times, and you get this

00:20:54.194 --> 00:20:55.048
pattern.
 

00:20:55.048 --> 00:20:59.217
Each time you throw the die and
ask where will the photon land,

00:20:59.217 --> 00:21:03.182
this function is waiting to
tell you the probability it will

00:21:03.182 --> 00:21:04.460
land somewhere.
 

00:21:04.460 --> 00:21:06.490
So we have to play this game in
two ways.

00:21:06.490 --> 00:21:09.805
It is particles,
but its future is determined by

00:21:09.805 --> 00:21:10.440
a wave.
 

00:21:10.440 --> 00:21:12.430
The wave is purely mathematical.
 

00:21:12.430 --> 00:21:15.329
You cannot put an instrument
that measures the energy due to

00:21:15.329 --> 00:21:15.920
that wave.
 

00:21:15.920 --> 00:21:20.273
It's a construct we use to
determine what will happen in

00:21:20.273 --> 00:21:21.700
this experiment.
 

00:21:21.700 --> 00:21:24.843
So we have no trouble
predicting this experiment,

00:21:24.843 --> 00:21:27.660
but we only make statistical
predictions.

00:21:27.660 --> 00:21:30.290
So if someone tells you,
"I got light from some

00:21:30.290 --> 00:21:33.325
mercury vapor or something,
it's got a certain wavelength,

00:21:33.325 --> 00:21:34.858
therefore a certain frequency.
 

00:21:34.858 --> 00:21:38.838
I'm going to take two slits and
I'm going to send the light from

00:21:38.838 --> 00:21:41.430
the left so weak that at a given
time,

00:21:41.430 --> 00:21:45.240
only one photon leaves the
source and hits the screen.

00:21:45.240 --> 00:21:47.098
What will happen?"
 

00:21:47.098 --> 00:21:49.538
We will say we don't know what
it will do.

00:21:49.538 --> 00:21:51.308
We don't know where it will
land.

00:21:51.308 --> 00:21:53.555
But we tell you if you do it
enough times,

00:21:53.555 --> 00:21:56.240
millions of times,
soon a pattern will develop.

00:21:56.240 --> 00:21:58.865
Namely, if you plot your
histogram on where everybody

00:21:58.865 --> 00:22:00.328
landed, you'll get a graph.
 

00:22:00.328 --> 00:22:02.980
It's the graph that I can
predict.

00:22:02.980 --> 00:22:04.500
And how do I predict that graph.
 

00:22:04.500 --> 00:22:09.070
I say, "What was the
energy momentum of your

00:22:09.070 --> 00:22:10.500
photon?"
 

00:22:10.500 --> 00:22:15.141
If it was p,
I will introduce a wave whose

00:22:15.141 --> 00:22:19.298
momentum is
2pℏ/p.

00:22:19.298 --> 00:22:20.969
Oh, I'm sorry,
I forgot to tell you guys one

00:22:20.969 --> 00:22:21.279
thing.
 

00:22:21.279 --> 00:22:21.980
I apologize.
 

00:22:21.980 --> 00:22:25.180
I've been writing
ℏ and h.

00:22:25.180 --> 00:22:28.935
I should have mentioned it long
back, ℏ is

00:22:28.935 --> 00:22:30.318
h/2p.
 

00:22:30.318 --> 00:22:32.733
Since the combination occurs so
often, people write

00:22:32.733 --> 00:22:33.700
ℏ.
 

00:22:33.700 --> 00:22:37.338
So you can write l =
2pℏ/p,

00:22:37.338 --> 00:22:38.380
or h/p.
 

00:22:38.380 --> 00:22:40.309
It doesn't matter.
 

00:22:40.309 --> 00:22:41.640
So I've stopped using h.
 

00:22:41.640 --> 00:22:44.750
Most people now in the business
use ℏ,

00:22:44.750 --> 00:22:47.509
because the energy is
ℏw,

00:22:47.509 --> 00:22:49.798
the momentum is
ℏk.

00:22:49.798 --> 00:22:51.857
If you want,
you can write this

00:22:51.857 --> 00:22:55.700
2phk and k
is 2p/l.

00:22:55.700 --> 00:22:57.818
Then you find p is
h/l.

00:22:57.818 --> 00:23:00.559
That's how some people used to
write it in the old days,

00:23:00.559 --> 00:23:03.798
but now we write it in terms of
ℏ and k.

00:23:03.798 --> 00:23:08.417
Anyway, I can make these
predictions, if I knew the

00:23:08.417 --> 00:23:10.818
momentum of the photons.
 

00:23:10.818 --> 00:23:12.728
The photons were of a definite
momentum, therefore there's a

00:23:12.728 --> 00:23:13.440
definite wavelength.
 

00:23:13.440 --> 00:23:19.000
I can predict the interference
pattern.

00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:22.339
So where is the photon when it
goes from start to finish?

00:23:22.339 --> 00:23:23.108
We don't know.
 

00:23:23.108 --> 00:23:25.220
I'll come back to that question
now.

00:23:25.220 --> 00:23:29.142
But I want to mention to you a
historical fact,

00:23:29.142 --> 00:23:33.236
which is, photons were not
really found this way,

00:23:33.236 --> 00:23:37.500
by looking at the recoil of an
emulsion plate.

00:23:37.500 --> 00:23:40.878
Just for completeness,
I'm going to make a five minute

00:23:40.878 --> 00:23:43.940
digression to tell you how
photons were found.

00:23:43.940 --> 00:23:46.160
So they were actually predicted
by Einstein.

00:23:46.160 --> 00:23:48.886
He got the Nobel Prize for
predicting the photon,

00:23:48.886 --> 00:23:52.067
rather than for the Theory of
Relativity, which was still

00:23:52.067 --> 00:23:53.828
controversial at that time.
 

00:23:53.828 --> 00:23:57.957
So he predicted the photons,
based on actually fairly

00:23:57.957 --> 00:24:02.720
complicated thermodynamic
statistical mechanics arguments.

00:24:02.720 --> 00:24:06.854
But one way to understand it is
in terms of what's called the

00:24:06.854 --> 00:24:08.440
photoelectric effect.
 

00:24:08.440 --> 00:24:12.375
If you take a metal and you say
"Where are the electrons in

00:24:12.375 --> 00:24:13.500
the metal?"
 

00:24:13.500 --> 00:24:17.470
As you know most electrons are
orbiting the parent nucleus.

00:24:17.470 --> 00:24:20.710
But in a metal,
some electrons are communal.

00:24:20.710 --> 00:24:24.430
Each atom donates one or two
electrons to the whole metal.

00:24:24.430 --> 00:24:26.700
They can run all over the metal.
 

00:24:26.700 --> 00:24:29.400
They don't have to be near
their parent nucleus.

00:24:29.400 --> 00:24:31.369
They cannot leave the metal.
 

00:24:31.369 --> 00:24:33.450
So in a way, they are like this.
 

00:24:33.450 --> 00:24:36.734
There's a little tank whose
depth is h,

00:24:36.734 --> 00:24:40.460
and let's say mgh I want
to call W.

00:24:40.460 --> 00:24:44.069
So these guys are somewhere in
the bottom.

00:24:44.069 --> 00:24:48.568
They can run around;
they cannot get out.

00:24:48.568 --> 00:24:51.998
So if you want to yank an
electron out of the metal,

00:24:51.998 --> 00:24:54.954
you have to give an energy
equal to W,

00:24:54.954 --> 00:24:57.509
which is called the work
function.

00:24:57.509 --> 00:25:00.740
So how are you going to get an
electron to acquire some energy?

00:25:00.740 --> 00:25:01.480
We all know.
 

00:25:01.480 --> 00:25:03.608
Electron is an electric charge.
 

00:25:03.608 --> 00:25:06.386
I have to apply an electric
field and I know electromagnetic

00:25:06.386 --> 00:25:08.930
waves are nothing but electric
and magnetic fields,

00:25:08.930 --> 00:25:11.960
so I shine a light,
a source of light,

00:25:11.960 --> 00:25:13.528
towards this.
 

00:25:13.528 --> 00:25:16.281
The electric field comes and
grabs the electron and shakes it

00:25:16.281 --> 00:25:16.650
loose.
 

00:25:16.650 --> 00:25:19.808
Hopefully it will shake it
loose from the metal,

00:25:19.808 --> 00:25:22.230
giving it enough energy to
escape.

00:25:22.230 --> 00:25:26.650
And once it escapes,
it can take off.

00:25:26.650 --> 00:25:30.607
So they took some light source
and they aimed it at the metal,

00:25:30.607 --> 00:25:32.619
to see if electrons come out.
 

00:25:32.619 --> 00:25:35.038
They didn't.
 

00:25:35.038 --> 00:25:41.490
So what do you think you will
do to get some action?

00:25:41.490 --> 00:25:42.009
Yes?
 

00:25:42.009 --> 00:25:44.578
Student: 
&gt;

00:25:44.578 --> 00:25:46.269
Prof: So you make it
brighter.

00:25:46.269 --> 00:25:47.657
You say, "Okay,
let me crank up--"

00:25:47.657 --> 00:25:48.660
that's what anybody would do.
 

00:25:48.660 --> 00:25:51.496
They cranked up the intensity
of light, make it brighter and

00:25:51.496 --> 00:25:52.650
brighter and brighter.
 

