00:31:25.328 --> 00:31:29.807
Anyway, Compton said the
following thing - it turns out

00:31:29.807 --> 00:31:34.366
that if you have an electron
here and you send a beam of

00:31:34.366 --> 00:31:37.248
light,
it scatters off the electron

00:31:37.248 --> 00:31:41.465
and comes off in some direction
at an angle q to the original

00:31:41.465 --> 00:31:42.380
direction.
 

00:31:42.380 --> 00:31:48.154
The wavelength here changes by
an amount Dl,

00:31:48.154 --> 00:31:53.351
and Dl happens to be
2pℏ

00:31:53.351 --> 00:31:58.779
/mc x 1 - cosine
q.

00:31:58.779 --> 00:31:59.808
Are you with me?
 

00:31:59.808 --> 00:32:03.240
You send light in at a known
wavelength.

00:32:03.240 --> 00:32:06.076
It scatters off the electron
and comes at an angle q,

00:32:06.076 --> 00:32:09.020
no longer preserving its
wavelength, having a different

00:32:09.020 --> 00:32:09.838
wavelength.
 

00:32:09.838 --> 00:32:13.199
And the shift in the wavelength
is connected to the angle of

00:32:13.199 --> 00:32:13.940
scattering.
 

00:32:13.940 --> 00:32:16.335
For example,
