00:32:23.980 --> 00:32:29.210
And you can find the l of it by
putting a diffraction grating.

00:32:29.210 --> 00:32:35.015
Now, what one could show is
that if you took this to be made

00:32:35.015 --> 00:32:37.865
of particles,
and each particle has an

00:32:37.865 --> 00:32:40.788
energy, ℏw,
and each particle has a

00:32:40.788 --> 00:32:44.405
momentum, ℏk,
and that that collides with an

00:32:44.405 --> 00:32:46.906
electron,
then you just balance energy

00:32:46.906 --> 00:32:49.558
conservation and momentum
conservation.

00:32:49.558 --> 00:32:52.148
In any collision,
energy and momentum before =

00:32:52.148 --> 00:32:53.759
energy and momentum after.
 

00:32:53.759 --> 00:32:55.790
You set them equal and you
fiddle around,

00:32:55.790 --> 00:32:58.279
you can find the new momentum
after scattering.

00:32:58.279 --> 00:33:00.547
From the new momentum,
you can extract the new

00:33:00.547 --> 00:33:03.519
wavelength and you will find
this formula actually works.

00:33:03.519 --> 00:33:07.404
So I did that in Physics 200,
I think, so if you want,

00:33:07.404 --> 00:33:11.509
you can go look at that,
or maybe it was done for you.

00:33:11.509 --> 00:33:12.000
I don't know.
 

00:33:12.000 --> 00:33:15.538
But Compton's scattering,
the scattering due to Compton,

00:33:15.538 --> 00:33:19.310
can be completely understood if
you think of the incoming beam

00:33:19.310 --> 00:33:22.959
of light as made up of particles
with that momentum and that

00:33:22.959 --> 00:33:23.640
energy.
 

00:33:23.640 --> 00:33:26.307
In other words,
you're always going to go back

00:33:26.307 --> 00:33:27.019
and forth.
 

00:33:27.019 --> 00:33:30.578
Light will be characterized by
a wavelength and by a momentum.

00:33:30.578 --> 00:33:34.368
It will be characterized by a
frequency and by an energy.

00:33:34.368 --> 00:33:36.635
When you think about the
particles, you'll think of the

00:33:36.635 --> 00:33:37.558
energy and momentum.
 

00:33:37.558 --> 00:33:41.840
When you think about the waves,
you'll think of frequency and

00:33:41.840 --> 00:33:42.838
wave number.
 

00:33:42.838 --> 00:33:45.190
So this is what really nailed
it.

00:33:45.190 --> 00:33:51.000
After this, you could not doubt
the reality of the photons.

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:55.829
Okay, now I go back to my old
story.

00:33:55.829 --> 00:33:57.420
Let's remember what it is.
 

00:33:57.420 --> 00:34:00.891
The shock is that light,
which we were willing to

00:34:00.891 --> 00:34:03.528
believe was waves,
because Young had done the

00:34:03.528 --> 00:34:06.576
interference experiment,
is actually made up of

00:34:06.576 --> 00:34:07.539
particles.
 

00:34:07.539 --> 00:34:08.840
That's the first thing.
 

00:34:08.840 --> 00:34:10.550
So who needs the wave?
 

00:34:10.550 --> 00:34:13.003
If you send a single photon
into a double slit,

00:34:13.003 --> 00:34:14.710
we don't know what it will do.
 

00:34:14.710 --> 00:34:17.050
We can only give the odds.
 

00:34:17.050 --> 00:34:20.233
To find the odds,
we take the photon's wavelength

00:34:20.233 --> 00:34:23.021
and we form this wave,
and then we form the

00:34:23.021 --> 00:34:24.679
interference pattern.
 

00:34:24.679 --> 00:34:28.393
And we find out that whenever
it is high, it is very likely to

00:34:28.393 --> 00:34:28.820
come.
 

00:34:28.820 --> 00:34:31.085
Wherever it's low,
it's very unlikely,

00:34:31.085 --> 00:34:32.679
but at 0, it won't come.
 

00:34:32.679 --> 00:34:35.181
So to test this theory,
it's not enough to send 1

00:34:35.181 --> 00:34:35.650
photon.
 

00:34:35.650 --> 00:34:39.260
1 photon may come here;
that doesn't show you anything.

00:34:39.260 --> 00:34:42.293
You've got to send millions of
photons, because if a prediction

00:34:42.293 --> 00:34:44.494
is probabilistic,
to test it, you've got to do

00:34:44.494 --> 00:34:45.230
many times.
 

00:34:45.230 --> 00:34:47.768
If I give you a coin,
and I tell you it's a fair

00:34:47.768 --> 00:34:50.739
coin, I toss it a couple of
times and I get 1 head and 1

00:34:50.739 --> 00:34:52.630
tail, it doesn't mean anything.
 

00:34:52.630 --> 00:34:55.219
You want to toss it 500,000
times and see if roughly half

00:34:55.219 --> 00:34:57.579
the time it's heads and half the
time it's tails.

00:34:57.579 --> 00:35:00.119
That's when a probabilistic
theory is verified.

00:35:00.119 --> 00:35:02.980
It's not verified by
individuals.

00:35:02.980 --> 00:35:06.436
Insurance companies are always
drawing pictures of when I'm

00:35:06.436 --> 00:35:07.329
going to die.
 

00:35:07.329 --> 00:35:12.090
They've got some plot,
and that's my average chance.

00:35:12.090 --> 00:35:15.123
I don't know when I will be
part of that statistic,

00:35:15.123 --> 00:35:18.340
because in fact--sorry,
it usually looks like this.

00:35:18.340 --> 00:35:22.007
Life expectancy of people looks
like that, but doesn't mean

00:35:22.007 --> 00:35:23.780
everybody dies at one day.
 

00:35:23.780 --> 00:35:27.367
People are dying left and
right, so there's probability on

00:35:27.367 --> 00:35:28.250
either side.
 

00:35:28.250 --> 00:35:31.440
So to verify this table that
companies have got,

00:35:31.440 --> 00:35:34.018
you have to watch a huge
population.

00:35:34.018 --> 00:35:36.760
Then you can do the histogram
and then you get the profile.

00:35:36.760 --> 00:35:40.474
So whenever you do statistical
theories, you've got to run it

00:35:40.474 --> 00:35:41.280
many times.
 

00:35:41.280 --> 00:35:43.349
I'll tell you more about
statistics and quantum

00:35:43.349 --> 00:35:43.889
mechanics.
 

00:35:43.889 --> 00:35:46.529
It's different from statistics
and classical mechanics and

00:35:46.529 --> 00:35:47.780
we'll come to that later.
 

00:35:47.780 --> 00:35:50.197
But for now,
you must understand the

00:35:50.197 --> 00:35:52.340
peculiar behavior of photons.
 

00:35:52.340 --> 00:35:55.126
They are not particles
entirely, they are not waves

00:35:55.126 --> 00:35:55.739
entirely.
 

00:35:55.739 --> 00:35:59.099
They are particles in the sense
they're localized energy and

00:35:59.099 --> 00:36:02.460
momentum, but they don't travel
like Newtonian particles.

00:36:02.460 --> 00:36:04.755
If they were Newtonian
particles, you'll never

00:36:04.755 --> 00:36:07.967
understand why opening a second
slit reduced the amount of light

00:36:07.967 --> 00:36:09.039
coming somewhere.
 

00:36:09.039 --> 00:36:10.900
All right, so this is the story.
 

00:36:10.900 --> 00:36:15.159
So now comes the French
physicist,

00:36:15.159 --> 00:36:19.592
de Broglie, and he argued as
follows - you'll find his

00:36:19.592 --> 00:36:24.353
argument quite persuasive,
and this is what he did for his

00:36:24.353 --> 00:36:24.730
PhD.
 

00:36:24.730 --> 00:36:29.585
He said, "If light,
which I thought was a

00:36:29.585 --> 00:36:32.333
particle--
I'm sorry, which I thought was

00:36:32.333 --> 00:36:34.056
a wave,
is actually made up of

00:36:34.056 --> 00:36:37.159
particles, perhaps things which
I always thought of as

00:36:37.159 --> 00:36:39.282
particles,
like electrons,

00:36:39.282 --> 00:36:42.760
have a wave associated with
them."

00:36:42.760 --> 00:36:45.309
And he said,
"Let me postulate that

00:36:45.309 --> 00:36:48.904
electrons also have a wave
associated with them and that

00:36:48.904 --> 00:36:52.956
the wavelength associated with
an electron of momentum p

00:36:52.956 --> 00:36:56.289
will be 2pℏ
/p;

00:36:56.289 --> 00:37:01.159
and that this wave will produce
the same interference pattern

00:37:01.159 --> 00:37:06.110
when you do it with electrons,
as you did with light."

00:37:06.110 --> 00:37:07.500
So what does that mean?
 

00:37:07.500 --> 00:37:11.239
It means if you did a double
slit experiment,

00:37:11.239 --> 00:37:13.809
and you sent electrons of
momentum p,

00:37:13.809 --> 00:37:16.070
one at a time,
and you sit here with an

00:37:16.070 --> 00:37:20.085
electron detector,
or you have an array of

00:37:20.085 --> 00:37:25.418
electron detectors,
he claims that the pattern will

00:37:25.418 --> 00:37:29.373
look like this,
where this pattern is obtained

00:37:29.373 --> 00:37:34.282
by using a certain wavelength
that corresponds to the momentum

00:37:34.282 --> 00:37:37.260
of the incoming beam of
electrons.

00:37:37.260 --> 00:37:40.516
Now there the shock is not that
the electron hits one point on

00:37:40.516 --> 00:37:41.210
the screen.
 

00:37:41.210 --> 00:37:43.389
It supposed to;
it's a particle.

00:37:43.389 --> 00:37:46.268
What is shocking is that when
two slits are open,

00:37:46.268 --> 00:37:49.869
you don't get any electrons in
the location where you used to

00:37:49.869 --> 00:37:50.949
get electrons.
 

00:37:50.949 --> 00:37:54.226
That is the surprising thing,
because if an electron is a

00:37:54.226 --> 00:37:58.090
Newtonian particle and you used
to go like that through hole 1,

00:37:58.090 --> 00:38:00.389
and you used to go like that
through hole 2,

00:38:00.389 --> 00:38:02.150
if you open the two holes and
two slits,

00:38:02.150 --> 00:38:06.289
you've got to get the sum of
the two numbers.

00:38:06.289 --> 00:38:10.170
You cannot escape that,
because in Newtonian mechanics,

00:38:10.170 --> 00:38:14.409
an electron either goes through
slit 1 or through slit 2.

00:38:14.409 --> 00:38:16.320
And therefore,
the number coming here is

00:38:16.320 --> 00:38:19.259
simply the sum of the ones that
went here, the ones that went

00:38:19.259 --> 00:38:19.699
here.
 

00:38:19.699 --> 00:38:22.219
Now sometimes people think,
"Well,

00:38:22.219 --> 00:38:24.768
if you have a lot of electrons
coming here,

00:38:24.768 --> 00:38:28.443
maybe these guys bumped into
these guys and collided and

00:38:28.443 --> 00:38:32.050
therefore didn't hit the screen
at that point."

00:38:32.050 --> 00:38:33.369
That's a fake.
 

00:38:33.369 --> 00:38:35.409
You know you don't have much of
a chance with that explanation,

00:38:35.409 --> 00:38:37.110
because if there are random
collisions,

00:38:37.110 --> 00:38:39.010
what are the odds they'll form
this beautiful,

00:38:39.010 --> 00:38:40.539
repeatable pattern?
 

00:38:40.539 --> 00:38:42.199
Not very big.
 

00:38:42.199 --> 00:38:44.719
Furthermore,
you can silence that criticism

00:38:44.719 --> 00:38:48.380
by making the electron gun that
emits electrons so feeble that

00:38:48.380 --> 00:38:51.309
at a given time,
there's only one electron.

00:38:51.309 --> 00:38:53.340
There's only one electron in
the lab.

00:38:53.340 --> 00:38:55.710
It left here,
then it arrived there.

00:38:55.710 --> 00:38:57.809
And it cannot collide with
itself.

00:38:57.809 --> 00:39:02.599
And yet it knows two slits are
open.

00:39:02.599 --> 00:39:07.150
A Newtonian particle cannot
know that two slits are open.

00:39:07.150 --> 00:39:11.733
So it has an associated wave,
and if you do this calculation

00:39:11.733 --> 00:39:16.315
and you find the interference
pattern, that's what electrons

00:39:16.315 --> 00:39:16.860
do.
 

00:39:16.860 --> 00:39:18.980
Originally, it was not done
with a double slit.

00:39:18.980 --> 00:39:20.210
It was done with a crystal.
 

00:39:20.210 --> 00:39:23.858
I have given you one homework
problem where you can see how a

00:39:23.858 --> 00:39:27.324
crystal of atoms regularly
arranged can also help you find

00:39:27.324 --> 00:39:29.210
the wavelength of anything.
 

00:39:29.210 --> 00:39:31.940
And you shine a beam of
electrons on a crystal,

00:39:31.940 --> 00:39:35.280
you find out that they come out
in only one particular angle,

00:39:35.280 --> 00:39:37.059
and using the angle,
you can find the wavelength,

00:39:37.059 --> 00:39:39.559
and the wavelength agrees with
the momentum.

00:39:39.559 --> 00:39:40.800
The momentum of the electron is
known,

00:39:40.800 --> 00:39:44.492
because if you accelerate them
between two plates with a

00:39:44.492 --> 00:39:47.420
certain voltage,
V, and the electron

00:39:47.420 --> 00:39:50.878
drops down the voltage,
it gains an energy eV,

00:39:50.878 --> 00:39:53.070
which is ½
mv^(2),

00:39:53.070 --> 00:39:56.030
which you can also write as
p^(2)/2m.

00:39:56.030 --> 00:40:00.992
So you can find the momentum of
an electron before you send it

00:40:00.992 --> 00:40:01.400
in.
 

00:40:01.400 --> 00:40:07.730
Okay, so this is the
peculiarity of particles now.

00:40:07.730 --> 00:40:13.289
Electron also behaves like a
particle or a wave.

00:40:13.289 --> 00:40:19.389
So now you can ask yourself the
following question.

00:40:19.389 --> 00:40:22.360
Why is it that microscopic
bodies--first of all,

00:40:22.360 --> 00:40:25.329
I hope you understand how
surprising this is.

00:40:25.329 --> 00:40:26.590
Suppose it was not electrons.
 

00:40:26.590 --> 00:40:29.481
Suppose this was not an
electron gun,

00:40:29.481 --> 00:40:31.570
but a machine gun,
okay?

00:40:31.570 --> 00:40:34.179
And these are some concrete
barriers.

00:40:34.179 --> 00:40:38.480
The barrier has a hole in it
and that's you.

00:40:38.480 --> 00:40:42.378
They've tied you to the back
wall and they're firing bullets

00:40:42.378 --> 00:40:44.438
at you,
and you're of course very

00:40:44.438 --> 00:40:47.460
anxious when a friend of yours
comes along and says,

00:40:47.460 --> 00:40:49.389
"I want to help you."
 

00:40:49.389 --> 00:40:54.699
So let me do that.
 

00:40:54.699 --> 00:40:57.753
So you know that that's not a
friend, and if you do it with

00:40:57.753 --> 00:40:59.070
bullets, it won't help.
 

00:40:59.070 --> 00:41:00.320
You cannot reduce the number of
bullets.

00:41:00.320 --> 00:41:03.036
And why is it with
electrons--if instead of the big

00:41:03.036 --> 00:41:05.134
scenario,
we scale the whole thing down

00:41:05.134 --> 00:41:07.494
to atomic dimensions,
and you're talking about

00:41:07.494 --> 00:41:10.280
electrons and slits which are a
few micrometers away,

00:41:10.280 --> 00:41:13.590
why is it that with electrons,
you can do that?

00:41:13.590 --> 00:41:16.250
Why is it with bullets you
don't do that?

00:41:16.250 --> 00:41:21.940
The answer has to do with this
wavelength p.

00:41:21.940 --> 00:41:26.202
If you put for p,
m x v and you put

00:41:26.202 --> 00:41:30.309
for m the mass of a
cannonball or a bullet,

00:41:30.309 --> 00:41:35.168
say 1 kilogram,
you will find this wavelength

00:41:35.168 --> 00:41:37.820
is 10^(-27 )something.
 

00:41:37.820 --> 00:41:43.054
That means these oscillations
will have maybe 10^(20

00:41:43.054 --> 00:41:49.010
)oscillations per centimeter and
you cannot detect that.

00:41:49.010 --> 00:41:51.474
So oscillation,
the human eye cannot detect

00:41:51.474 --> 00:41:54.878
that, and everything else looks
like you're just adding the

00:41:54.878 --> 00:41:57.579
intensities, not adding the wave
function.

00:41:57.579 --> 00:42:00.985
It looks like the probabilities
are additive,

00:42:00.985 --> 00:42:04.469
and you don't see the
interference pattern.

00:42:04.469 --> 00:42:07.963
Now there's another very
interesting twist on this

00:42:07.963 --> 00:42:10.389
experiment, which is as follows.
 

00:42:10.389 --> 00:42:12.885
You go back to that experiment,
and you say,

00:42:12.885 --> 00:42:16.425
"Look, I do not buy this
notion that an electron does not

00:42:16.425 --> 00:42:17.820
go through one slit.
 

00:42:17.820 --> 00:42:18.750
I mean, come on.
 

00:42:18.750 --> 00:42:22.000
How can it not go through one
particular slit?"

00:42:22.000 --> 00:42:23.800
So here's what I'm going to do.
 

00:42:23.800 --> 00:42:28.610
I'm going to put a light bulb
here.

00:42:28.610 --> 00:42:31.409
I'm going to have the light
bulb look at the slit,

00:42:31.409 --> 00:42:35.315
and when this guy goes past,
I will see whether the guy went

00:42:35.315 --> 00:42:38.030
through this slit or through
that slit.

00:42:38.030 --> 00:42:40.289
Then there's no talk about
going through both slits or not

00:42:40.289 --> 00:42:42.710
going through a definite slit or
not having the trajectory.

00:42:42.710 --> 00:42:45.179
All that's wrong,
because I'm going to actually

00:42:45.179 --> 00:42:48.509
catch the electron in the act of
going through one or the other

00:42:48.509 --> 00:42:50.119
by putting a light source.
 

00:42:50.119 --> 00:42:52.217
So you put a light source,
and whenever it hits an

00:42:52.217 --> 00:42:54.869
electron, you will see a flash
and you will know whether it was

00:42:54.869 --> 00:42:56.239
near this hole or that hole.
 

00:42:56.239 --> 00:42:58.480
You make a tally.
 

00:42:58.480 --> 00:43:01.434
So you find that a certain
number went through hole 1,

00:43:01.434 --> 00:43:03.610
a certain number went through
hole 2.

00:43:03.610 --> 00:43:05.590
You add them up,
you get the number,

00:43:05.590 --> 00:43:07.739
you cannot avoid getting the
number.

00:43:07.739 --> 00:43:12.768
Let's imagine that of our 1,000
electrons, about 20 got by

00:43:12.768 --> 00:43:15.150
without your seeing them.
 

00:43:15.150 --> 00:43:15.860
It can happen.
 

00:43:15.860 --> 00:43:17.489
When you turn the light,
you don't see it;

00:43:17.489 --> 00:43:19.820
it misses.
 

00:43:19.820 --> 00:43:24.400
Then you will find a pattern
that looks like this.

00:43:24.400 --> 00:43:29.902
There'll be a 2 percent wiggle
on top of this featureless

00:43:29.902 --> 00:43:30.690
curve.
 

00:43:30.690 --> 00:43:33.219
In other words,
the electrons that you caught

00:43:33.219 --> 00:43:36.210
and identified as going through
slit 1 or slit 2,

00:43:36.210 --> 00:43:39.829
their numbers add up the way
they do in Newtonian mechanics,

00:43:39.829 --> 00:43:42.119
but the electrons you did not
catch,

00:43:42.119 --> 00:43:45.045
who slipped by,
pretend as if they went through

00:43:45.045 --> 00:43:48.525
both the slits,
or at least they showed the

00:43:48.525 --> 00:43:50.429
interference pattern.
 

00:43:50.429 --> 00:43:53.063
That's a very novel thing,
that whether you see the

00:43:53.063 --> 00:43:55.329
electron or not,
makes such a difference.

00:43:55.329 --> 00:43:56.429
That's all I did.
 

00:43:56.429 --> 00:43:58.760
In one case,
I caught the electron.

00:43:58.760 --> 00:44:00.119
In the other case, I slipped by.
 

00:44:00.119 --> 00:44:04.755
And whenever it's not observed,
it seems to be able to somehow

00:44:04.755 --> 00:44:06.579
be aware of two slits.
 

00:44:06.579 --> 00:44:09.990
And this was a big surprise,
because normally when we study

00:44:09.990 --> 00:44:13.751
anything in Newtonian mechanics,
you say here's a collision,

00:44:13.751 --> 00:44:17.159
ball 1 collides and goes there,
you do all the calculations.

00:44:17.159 --> 00:44:19.510
Meanwhile, we are watching it.
 

00:44:19.510 --> 00:44:20.920
Maybe we are not watching it.
 

00:44:20.920 --> 00:44:21.800
Who cares?
 

00:44:21.800 --> 00:44:24.260
The answer doesn't depend on
whether we are watching or not?

00:44:24.260 --> 00:44:25.800
For example,
if you have a football game,

00:44:25.800 --> 00:44:28.030
and somebody throws the pass,
and you close your eyes,

00:44:28.030 --> 00:44:30.253
which sometimes my kids do,
because they don't know what's

00:44:30.253 --> 00:44:32.601
happening,
that doesn't change the outcome

00:44:32.601 --> 00:44:33.730
of the experiment.
 

00:44:33.730 --> 00:44:36.000
It follows its own trajectory.
 

00:44:36.000 --> 00:44:38.940
So what does seeing do to
anything?

00:44:38.940 --> 00:44:42.327
And you can say maybe he didn't
see it, but maybe people in the

00:44:42.327 --> 00:44:44.460
stadium were looking at the
football.

00:44:44.460 --> 00:44:46.820
So turn off all the lights.
 

00:44:46.820 --> 00:44:49.594
Then does the football have a
definite trajectory from start

00:44:49.594 --> 00:44:50.159
to finish?
 

00:44:50.159 --> 00:44:54.719
It does, because it's colliding
with all these air molecules.

00:44:54.719 --> 00:44:56.731
To remove all the air
molecules, of course,

00:44:56.731 --> 00:44:59.365
first you remove all the
spectators, then you remove all

00:44:59.365 --> 00:45:00.420
the air molecules.
 

00:45:00.420 --> 00:45:02.000
Then does it have a definite
trajectory?

00:45:02.000 --> 00:45:03.429
You might say,
"Of course it does.

00:45:03.429 --> 00:45:04.949
What difference does it
make?"

00:45:04.949 --> 00:45:07.230
But then you would be wrong.
 

00:45:07.230 --> 00:45:09.449
You would be wrong to think it
had a trajectory,

00:45:09.449 --> 00:45:11.900
because the minute you said it
had a trajectory,

00:45:11.900 --> 00:45:14.039
you will never understand
interference,

00:45:14.039 --> 00:45:16.590
which even a football can show.
 

00:45:16.590 --> 00:45:19.099
But the condition is,
for a football to show this

00:45:19.099 --> 00:45:21.869
kind of quantum effects,
it should not be disturbed by

00:45:21.869 --> 00:45:22.550
anything.
 

00:45:22.550 --> 00:45:24.849
It should not be seen.
 

00:45:24.849 --> 00:45:27.139
Nothing can collide with it.
 

00:45:27.139 --> 00:45:30.155
The minute you interact with a
quantum system,

00:45:30.155 --> 00:45:33.974
it stops doing this wishy-washy
business of "Where am

00:45:33.974 --> 00:45:34.780
I?"
 

00:45:34.780 --> 00:45:36.650
Till you see it,
it's not anywhere.

00:45:36.650 --> 00:45:38.849
Once you see it,
it's in a different location.

00:45:38.849 --> 00:45:41.079
Till you see it,
it's not taking any particular

00:45:41.079 --> 00:45:41.420
path.
 

00:45:41.420 --> 00:45:44.550
To assume it took this or that
path is simply wrong.

00:45:44.550 --> 00:45:47.840
But the act of observation
nails it.

00:45:47.840 --> 00:45:50.119
So why is observation so
important?

00:45:50.119 --> 00:45:52.050
You have to ask how we observe
things.

00:45:52.050 --> 00:45:53.900
We shine light.
 

00:45:53.900 --> 00:45:56.617
You've already seen,
the light is made of quanta,

00:45:56.617 --> 00:45:59.675
and each quantum carries a
certain momentum and certain

00:45:59.675 --> 00:46:00.300
energy.
 

00:46:00.300 --> 00:46:05.000
If I want to locate the
electron with some waves,

00:46:05.000 --> 00:46:07.641
with some light,
I want the momentum of the

00:46:07.641 --> 00:46:10.193
light to be weak,
because I don't want to slam

00:46:10.193 --> 00:46:12.409
the electron too hard in the act
of finding it.

00:46:12.409 --> 00:46:14.429
So I want p to be very
small.

00:46:14.429 --> 00:46:17.768
If p is very small,
l,

00:46:17.768 --> 00:46:20.340
which is 2pℏ
/p becomes large,

00:46:20.340 --> 00:46:23.780
and once l's bigger than
the spacing between the slits,

00:46:23.780 --> 00:46:25.869
the picture you get will be so
fuzzy,

00:46:25.869 --> 00:46:28.619
you cannot tell which slit it
went through.

00:46:28.619 --> 00:46:31.152
In other words,
to make a fine observation in

00:46:31.152 --> 00:46:34.320
optics, you need a wavelength
smaller than the distances

00:46:34.320 --> 00:46:35.989
you're trying to resolve.
 

00:46:35.989 --> 00:46:38.710
So you've got to use a
wavelength smaller than these

00:46:38.710 --> 00:46:39.349
two slits.
 

00:46:39.349 --> 00:46:44.204
So this p should be such
that this l is comparable

00:46:44.204 --> 00:46:46.670
to this slit,
or even smaller.

00:46:46.670 --> 00:46:50.650
But then you will find the act
of observing the electron

00:46:50.650 --> 00:46:53.980
imparts to it an unknown amount
of momentum.

00:46:53.980 --> 00:46:58.476
Once you change the momentum,
you change the interference

00:46:58.476 --> 00:46:59.280
pattern.
 

00:46:59.280 --> 00:47:03.639
So the act of observation,
which is pretty innocuous for

00:47:03.639 --> 00:47:06.942
you and me--
right now, I'm getting slammed

00:47:06.942 --> 00:47:11.300
by millions of photons,
but I'm taking it like a man.

00:47:11.300 --> 00:47:13.610
But for the electron,
it is not that simple.

00:47:13.610 --> 00:47:16.760
One collision with a photon is
like getting hit by a truck.

00:47:16.760 --> 00:47:19.827
The momentum of the photon is
enormous in the scale of the

00:47:19.827 --> 00:47:20.420
electron.
 

00:47:20.420 --> 00:47:22.550
So it matters a lot to the
electron.

00:47:22.550 --> 00:47:24.199
For example,
when I observe you,

00:47:24.199 --> 00:47:26.860
I see you because photons
bounce back and forth.

00:47:26.860 --> 00:47:29.925
Suppose it's a dark room and I
was swinging one of those things

00:47:29.925 --> 00:47:31.409
you see in Gladiator.
 

00:47:31.409 --> 00:47:32.630
What's that thing called?
 

00:47:32.630 --> 00:47:33.909
Trying to locate you.
 

00:47:33.909 --> 00:47:36.663
So the act of location,
you realize it will be

00:47:36.663 --> 00:47:39.355
memorable for you,
because it's a destructive

00:47:39.355 --> 00:47:40.090
process.
 

00:47:40.090 --> 00:47:43.628
But in Newtonian mechanics,
we can imagine finding gentler

00:47:43.628 --> 00:47:47.228
ways to observe somebody and
there's no limit to how gentle

00:47:47.228 --> 00:47:47.849
it is.
 

00:47:47.849 --> 00:47:51.092
You just say make the light
dimmer and dimmer and dimmer

00:47:51.092 --> 00:47:52.920
till the person doesn't care.
 

00:47:52.920 --> 00:47:56.489
But in quantum theory,
it's not how dim the light is.

00:47:56.489 --> 00:47:59.197
If the light is too dim,
there are too few photons and

00:47:59.197 --> 00:48:00.730
nobody catches the electron.
 

00:48:00.730 --> 00:48:03.480
In order to see the electron,
you've got to send enough

00:48:03.480 --> 00:48:03.989
photons.
 

00:48:03.989 --> 00:48:07.161
But the point is,
each one carries a punch which

00:48:07.161 --> 00:48:08.039
is minimum.
 

00:48:08.039 --> 00:48:10.965
It cannot be smaller than this
number, because if the

00:48:10.965 --> 00:48:14.342
wavelength is bigger than this,
you cannot tell which hole it

00:48:14.342 --> 00:48:15.300
went through.
 

00:48:15.300 --> 00:48:18.996
That's why in quantum theory,
the act of observation is very

00:48:18.996 --> 00:48:21.690
important, and it can change the
outcome.

00:48:21.690 --> 00:48:28.309
Okay, so what can we figure out
from this.

00:48:28.309 --> 00:48:32.474
Well, it looks like the act of
observing somehow affects the

00:48:32.474 --> 00:48:34.380
momentum of the electron.
 

00:48:34.380 --> 00:48:37.380
So people often say that's why,
when you try to measure the

00:48:37.380 --> 00:48:40.068
position of the electron,
you do something bad to the

00:48:40.068 --> 00:48:41.570
momentum of the electron.
 

00:48:41.570 --> 00:48:44.255
We change it,
because you need a large

00:48:44.255 --> 00:48:46.940
momentum to see it very
accurately.

00:48:46.940 --> 00:48:51.279
But that statement is partly
correct but partly incomplete

00:48:51.279 --> 00:48:53.639
and I'll tell you what it is.
 

00:48:53.639 --> 00:48:56.715
The trouble is not that you use
a high momentum photon to see an

00:48:56.715 --> 00:48:57.739
electron precisely.
 

00:48:57.739 --> 00:49:00.059
That's not a problem.
 

00:49:00.059 --> 00:49:02.664
The problem is that when it
bounces off the electron and

00:49:02.664 --> 00:49:04.893
comes back to you,
it would have changed,

00:49:04.893 --> 00:49:07.809
the momentum by an amount that
you cannot predict,

00:49:07.809 --> 00:49:10.239
and I'll tell you why that is
the case.

00:49:10.239 --> 00:49:14.516
So I told you long back that if
you have a hole and light comes

00:49:14.516 --> 00:49:18.032
in through it,
it doesn't go straight,

00:49:18.032 --> 00:49:21.637
it fans out,
that the profile of light looks

00:49:21.637 --> 00:49:22.409
like this.
 

00:49:22.409 --> 00:49:28.679
It spreads out and the angle by
which it spreads out obeys the

00:49:28.679 --> 00:49:32.380
condition dsinq =
l.

00:49:32.380 --> 00:49:35.360
Remember that part from wave
theory of light.

00:49:35.360 --> 00:49:39.114
Now here is the person trying
to catch an electron,

00:49:39.114 --> 00:49:41.969
which is somewhere around this
line.

00:49:41.969 --> 00:49:47.280
And he or she brings a
microscope that looks like this.

00:49:47.280 --> 00:49:51.617
Here's the opening of the
microscope, and you send some

00:49:51.617 --> 00:49:52.260
light.
 

00:49:52.260 --> 00:49:58.559
This opening of the microscope
has some extent d.

00:49:58.559 --> 00:50:05.610
Let's say it's got a sharp
opening here of width d.

00:50:05.610 --> 00:50:08.612
The light comes,
hits an electron,

00:50:08.612 --> 00:50:12.344
if it is there,
and goes right back to the

00:50:12.344 --> 00:50:13.710
microscope.
 

00:50:13.710 --> 00:50:16.519
If I see a flicker of reflected
light, I know the electron had

00:50:16.519 --> 00:50:18.456
to be somewhere here,
because if it's here,

00:50:18.456 --> 00:50:20.530
